    "body" : "@NicolasBarbulesco The version with the question marks is the real SQL. All JDBC drivers can accept queries in this format. Under the hood, the JDBC driver may reformat the query to match the DB&#39;s native placeholder format (e.g, Oracle and PostgreSQL will replace <code>?</code> with <code>:1</code>, <code>:2</code>, etc), and in some specific cases it may replace the bind placeholders with escaped values (some MySQL drivers do this). However, most DBs are capable of handling queries with placeholders natively."
  } ],
